{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569219","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569219"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:25:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:25:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21953"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"21953","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/21953"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.77,0.08,0.03,0.01,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14875"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105606"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"14875","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/14875"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21953"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88034"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1571"},{"type":"tags","id":"4146"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"4989"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5649"},{"type":"tags","id":"5689"},{"type":"tags","id":"11260"},{"type":"tags","id":"11525"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"11989"},{"type":"tags","id":"12798"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"38472"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38473"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38474"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38475"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38476"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40130"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40131"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105606","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105606"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 14-year-old girl presents to the General Practice clinic requesting oral contraception. She reports being in a relationship with her 25-year-old boyfriend for the past six months. Her boyfriend is a teacher aide at her school. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She lives with her parents and is in year 10 at school. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate action for the doctor to take?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Report the case to the child protection authorities","Provide oral contraception and take no further action","Inform the girl\u0027s parents","Inform the school principal","Counsel the girl on her legal status"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario describes a clear case of child sexual abuse that requires mandatory reporting. The 14-year-old patient is well below the legal age of consent (16-17 years across Australian jurisdictions), and her 25-year-old \u0027boyfriend\u0027 is in a position of authority as a teacher aide at her school, creating a significant power imbalance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReport the case to the child protection authorities\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate action. Healthcare providers are mandatory reporters and have a legal obligation to report suspected child sexual abuse to the relevant child protection authority. This relationship constitutes statutory rape and abuse of a position of authority, regardless of whether the girl believes the relationship is consensual.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProvide oral contraception and take no further action\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate and potentially negligent. While providing healthcare is important, ignoring the illegal and exploitative nature of this relationship fails to protect a vulnerable minor from ongoing harm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInform the girl\u0027s parents\u003C/strong\u003E may be appropriate after reporting, but should not be the first action. In some cases, informing parents before authorities could potentially place the child at further risk if there are complex family dynamics. The child protection authorities will coordinate appropriate family involvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInform the school principal\u003C/strong\u003E is not the most appropriate next action for the doctor. While the school should eventually be notified - this would be via child protection authorities and police, the legal obligation for the doctor is to report to child protection authorities who have the statutory power to investigate and intervene.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECounsel the girl on her legal status\u003C/strong\u003E alone is inadequate. While education about consent and legal rights is valuable, it does not fulfill the doctor\u0027s mandatory reporting obligations in a case of clear sexual exploitation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter making the mandatory report, the doctor should also consider the girl\u0027s healthcare needs, including potential screening for sexually transmitted infections and addressing contraception needs, while maintaining a supportive and non-judgmental approach to ensure ongoing engagement with healthcare services.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Healthcare providers have a mandatory obligation to report suspected sexual abuse of minors to child protection authorities.","Sexual activity between a minor and person in position of authority (e.g., teacher aide) constitutes abuse regardless of consent.","The legal age of consent for sexual intercourse in Australia varies between 16 and 17 years depending on state/territory jurisdiction."],"references":["Australian Institute of Family Studies. Age of consent laws in Australia [Internet]. Canberra (ACT): Australian Institute of Family Studies; [cited 2024 Dec 6]. Available from: https://aifs.gov.au/resources/resource-sheets/age-consent-laws-australia","Mathews B, Sanci LA. Doctors\u2019 criminal law duty to report consensual sexual activity between adolescents: legal and clinical issues. Med J Aust. 2021;215(3):163-165. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34275139/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88034"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21953"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88034","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88034"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-10T21:41:31+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-01T20:15:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14875"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105606"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","na